Open the command prompt with administrative privileges.
Type ntdsutil and press Enter.
Type roles and press Enter.
Type connections and press Enter.
Type connect to server <> and press Enter (destination server name where it is needed to be transfer)
Type quit and press Enter.
 
Next, we will transfer FSMO roles one by one with the corresponding command, as the case may be. After each Enter appears a confirmation window. Just click Yes to continue.
 
For Schema Master, type transfer schema master and press Enter.
For RID Master, type transfer rid master and press Enter.
For Domain Naming Master, type transfer naming master and press Enter.
For PDC Emulator, type transfer pdc and press Enter.
For Infrastructure Master, type transfer infrastructure master and press Enter.
 
 
For seizure : replace transfer with Seize in the above command
 
 
	TRANSFER FROM ONE DC TO ANOTHER: 
	 
		• Execute netdom query fsmo command on CMD to see which DC is the FSMO role owner. 
		• 
	 
		• FSMO roles transfer operation can be performed in different ways: GUID, or PowerShell (Move-ADDirectoryServerOperationMasterRole or NTDSUtil). 
		• GUID 
		• RID, PDC, and Infrastructure Master Roles: 
		• From the DC that's NOT the FSMO roles owner, go to Active Directory Users and Computers 
		• Right-click the domain > Select Operations Master > Click Change for each role in the tab 
		• 
	 
		• Domain Naming Master Role: 
		• Open Active Directory Domains and Trusts. 
		• Right-click Active Directory Domains and Trusts > Select Operations Masters > Click Change 
	 
		• Schema Master Role: 
		• Register the schmmgmt.dll file using regsvr32 schmmgmt.dll on CMD. 
		• Execute mmc command on CMD for the Console Root to open. 
		• Open Active Directory Schema snap-in, right-click Active Directory Schema, select Operations Masters, and click Change. 
	 
		• PowerShell 
		• NTDSUtil 
		• Enter NTDSUtil command on CMD. 
		• Log into the server that is NOT the owner of the FSMO roles. In this scenario, DC2. 
		• Transfer the role using the below command: 
		• 
	 
		• Move-ADDirectoryServerOperationMasterRole 
		• Go to PowerShell and enter the following cmdlet: Move-ADDirectoryServerOperationMasterRole -Identity <TargetServer> -OperationMasterRole SchemaMaster 
		• Target server should be the DC that is taking over the role. 
		• Commands for the FSMO roles as follows: 
		• PDCEmulator 
		• RIDMaster 
		• InfrastructureMaster 
		• DomainNamingMaster 
		• SchemaMaster 
	 
